			<section>
				<h2 class="lead"><u>Experience building a detector</u></h2>
				<p>
					From 2012 to 2015 I worked at <a target="_blank" href="https://www.jlab.org/">Thomas Jefferson National Accelerator Facility</a> (JLab). In that time I helped build the Forward Calorimeter or FCAL which is designed to measure the energy of particles that pass through lead glass blocks that are stacked in a circular array 59 rows high. Cherenkov light is radiated by the particle passing through the lead glass block and are collected on the other end by a photomultier tube or PMT. The Cherenkov light excites electrons in the PMT and by stacking metal plates at increasing voltage (as high at 2000 Volts) more electrons are generated. These devices are extremely sensitive to ambient light so it is critical that they operate in a totally dark enviornment. For this reason we built a darkroom to enclose our electronics after stacking each lead glass block assembly. 
