				<h3 class="lead"><u>Code developed for the FCAL</u></h3>
				<p>
					Like any project our codebase started out small and quickly grew as we wanted to monitor and test more things. The two programming languages I used were Perl and C++, which are the most common languages used in high energy physics, though Python is quickly growing. Since I was the primary developer for most of the FCAL code I created a few GitHub repos for other colleagues to use.
					<br><br>

					With Perl I could communicate to a MySQL database maintained by JLab called JInventory. In the case of the FCAL, we have over 10,0000 hardware components that all need an associated maintenance history record and must also be mapped to a physical location around the lab. The Perl scripts can be found <a target="_blank" href="https://github.com/manlara/FCAL_Scripts">here.</a>
					<br><br>

					C++ is the primary language of choice in scientific compting for high energy physics and is the language I have the most years of experience with. As I touched on previously, this detector converts light into a charge distribution whose integral is proportional to energy. On the face of the detector is plexiglass with remotely controlled led lights at each corner. The plexiglass is darkened on both side but the side that touches the face of the detector is sanded so that led light will diffract approximately uniformly. This is known as a light monitoring system which allows us to test the response of the PMT with a known light energy (from the led). To test performance of the detector I collected data with the light monitoring system and analayzed timing variations in the pulse peak and integral. The C++ code that accomplishes this task can be found <a target="_blank" href="https://github.com/manlara/FCALPpPi">here.</a>
				</p>
